tori — an offline archive of X (Twitter).

tori captures a corner of X — a profile, a thread, a search, your bookmarks or
likes — into a self-contained, offline-browsable repository: every tweet as a
record, the media localised, rendered into a static site and into Markdown,
with the original JSON kept beside each record as the source of truth.

tori builds its reads on the scraping engine of x (https://github.com/tamnd/x-cli),
which it imports directly: the no-auth syndication path, the guest- and
session-token GraphQL tiers, the one legacy tweet/user parser, the normalized
data model, the shared HTTP client, and the session store. It adds only the
archive-shaped pieces x never needed — media localisation, conversation
assembly, and the HTML and Markdown renderers.

x derives from Nitter (https://github.com/zedeus/nitter), in particular its
approach to X's web-client GraphQL API: the hardcoded public web bearer token,
the versioned GraphQL operation/query-id map, the guest-token activation flow,
the variables/features request shape, cursor pagination, and the shared
"legacy" tweet/user JSON model.

